  "body": "### What is wrong?\r\n\r\nI am finding the API for using `CancelToken` awkward and somewhat cumbersome.\r\n\r\n- Always have to import both `CancelToken` and `wait_with_token`\r\n- Many `wait_with_token` statements in a function body become repetitive.\r\n\r\n### How can it be fixed\r\n\r\nI see three options.\r\n\r\n#### 1. Add `CancelToken.wait_with` method\r\n\r\nThis would be a wrapper around the `wait_with_token` API that makes it so you only have to pass in the `*futures` argument.\r\n\r\nBenefit of this one is that it reduces the necessary imports to only the `CancelToken`\r\n\r\n#### 2. Add a `Cancelable` mixin base class.\r\n\r\n```python\r\nclass Cancelable:\r\n    CancelToken = CancelToken  # convenience API?\r\n    cancel_token: CancelToken = None\r\n    \r\n    def __init__(self, cancel_token):\r\n        self.cancel_token = cancel_token\r\n\r\n    async def wait_with_token(self, *futures, **kwargs):\r\n        return await wait_with_token(*futures, token=self.cancel_token, **kwargs)\r\n```\r\n\r\nBenefit of this one is that you only have to import the `Cancellable` class.  However, this approach only helps use of `CancelToken` in classes.\r\n\r\n#### 3. Make `wait_with_token` curry-able.\r\n\r\nThis makes use of cancel tokens in *functional* code easier to use.  A function body with *many* `await` statements can create a local curried `wait_with_token` and then call it only with the `*futures`.\r\n\r\nThis approach doesn't alleviate the need to import both the `CancelToken` and `wait_with_token` function.",
